d racism, fragmented policy, and intra-ethnic exploitation in the West. To overcome this legacy, Sarathy offers a number of proposals to improve the visibility and working conditions of pineros and to provide them with a stronger voice in immigration and forestry policy-making.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aForeign workers -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- United States. 0aForeign workers, Latin American -- Northwest, Pacific. 0aForests and forestry -- Employees -- Health and hygiene -- United States. 0aForests and forestry -- Employees -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- United States. 0aForests and forestry -- Employees. 0aWages -- Foreign workers -- United States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482115540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774821155423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774821155/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles